1
00:00:00,487 --> 00:00:25,971
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa

2
00:00:26,626 --> 00:00:37,465
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:37,585 --> 00:00:49,005
So, I thought we'd just have a little contemplation, you might say, around these three words, sympathy, empathy,

4
00:00:50,031 --> 00:00:50,832
and compassion.

5
00:00:51,414 --> 00:00:57,542
So I want to quote the Buddha here, talking about himself and his relationship to the monks.

6
00:00:58,765 --> 00:01:06,176
Thus, monks, I have taught you the unconditioned, the destination and the path leading to the destination.

7
00:01:07,137 --> 00:01:17,371
Whatever should be done, monks, by a compassionate teacher, out of compassion for his disciples, desiring their welfare, that I have done for you.

8
00:01:17,926 --> 00:01:44,540
these are the roots of trees monks these are empty huts meditate do not be negligent lest you regret it later this is my instruction to you now uh interestingly whenever he talks about compassion about himself as a compassionate person he always uses the word anukampa

9
00:01:45,382 --> 00:01:48,347
And this word means to tremble.

10
00:01:49,269 --> 00:01:56,042
So the anu is just a reinforcement, shaking, trembling.

11
00:01:56,061 --> 00:02:00,790
And it's what we would, I presume, recognize as empathy.

12
00:02:01,393 --> 00:02:06,882
So it's a sort of resonating with somebody else's heart, with somebody else's suffering.

13
00:02:08,888 --> 00:02:14,675
The usual word that you'll find, of course, is Karuna, which just means compassion.

14
00:02:14,996 --> 00:02:21,383
And he's often titled the Mahakaruniko, the great compassionate one.

15
00:02:21,403 --> 00:02:30,094
So if we look at these three words, the sympathy, I think it gets bad press these days, sympathy, in the caring professions.

16
00:02:30,115 --> 00:02:35,622
Well, you can understand that if you're looking after somebody, sympathy doesn't quite make it.

17
00:02:36,225 --> 00:02:41,231
But even in psychotherapy, I think they have a bit of a downer on it.

18
00:02:41,891 --> 00:02:47,758
But frankly, if you were going to feel empathetic about all the suffering in the world, I think you'd burn out.

19
00:02:49,061 --> 00:02:51,122
At least I think I'd burn out.

20
00:02:52,645 --> 00:02:58,671
The danger, of course, is that you're standing too far apart.

21
00:02:58,852 --> 00:03:01,574
You're not actually feeling anything.

22
00:03:01,943 --> 00:03:09,102
And this makes any expression of sympathy sound a bit false.

23
00:03:10,448 --> 00:03:19,897
And also, in that state, you could fall into the error of being judgmental about the person who's suffering.

24
00:03:20,618 --> 00:03:28,546
So if somebody fell off a ladder, you might say, oh, well, you shouldn't have put the ladder there at all.

25
00:03:28,586 --> 00:03:31,949
I mean, you were just asking for an accident.

26
00:03:32,450 --> 00:03:36,354
It doesn't particularly help somebody who's just broken their legs.

27
00:03:39,118 --> 00:04:01,532
so i think there's a place for sympathy i mean when when somebody dies you send a card with sympathies you don't send a card with empathies so i think it still has has some role to play in our relationship to suffering to people who are suffering if you hang about

28
00:04:01,731 --> 00:04:28,278
know certain facts about the world and you allow yourself to become empathetic then uh you know it's it's a big weight upon you because that empathy moves you towards action so a sympathy i think just has a place of a sort of mild connection a mild heart connection just knowing that there's not much you can do about it you know i mean at the moment for instance

29
00:04:28,377 --> 00:04:34,946
Every day, it seems, around about 40,000 children die of starvation or hunger-related causes.

30
00:04:35,807 --> 00:04:40,733
If you were to hang on to that, you know, it's a sort of a dreadful, awful figure.

31
00:04:41,435 --> 00:04:46,302
The Buddha in the Dhammapada actually says hunger is the worst of all diseases.

32
00:04:47,446 --> 00:04:50,711
I mean, we don't really feel hunger.

33
00:04:50,750 --> 00:04:55,598
We feel hungry, feel a bit peckish, but we're very quick to sort of fulfill it.

34
00:04:57,040 --> 00:05:11,343
But hunger, knowing hunger, you know, a sort of something that really begins to make you worry about your life, that we've never, or at least I've never had that sort of hunger.

35
00:05:11,745 --> 00:05:20,283
There was somebody who came to Kandaboda who said that he'd been out in the country and he'd lost his food.

36
00:05:20,322 --> 00:05:21,084
Something happened.

37
00:05:21,365 --> 00:05:22,185
This is in America.

38
00:05:22,927 --> 00:05:27,076
And he got so hungry that when he caught a bird, he just ate it.

39
00:05:27,336 --> 00:05:28,598
He ate it raw.

40
00:05:28,639 --> 00:05:33,247
I couldn't tell you how hungry you can get.

41
00:05:34,966 --> 00:05:43,302
So this sympathy comes from the Greek, which just means to have a feeling with, a community feeling actually, a sympathy.

42
00:05:44,966 --> 00:05:49,995
Empathy, of course, comes from the Greek as well, meaning in, in feeling.

43
00:05:50,475 --> 00:05:57,430
So you're actually much closer to the person in your heart.

44
00:05:57,747 --> 00:06:06,658
Now, I've got something from this social psychologist, Daniel Batson, who's researched empathy, it seems, for decades.

45
00:06:07,459 --> 00:06:09,461
And he says there are eight different concepts.

46
00:06:10,403 --> 00:06:14,767
So I'll read them through and you can decide which one you prefer.

47
00:06:15,509 --> 00:06:19,514
So the first one is knowing another's thoughts and feelings.

48
00:06:21,016 --> 00:06:24,699
That's how some people use empathy, knowing another's thoughts and feelings.

49
00:06:25,269 --> 00:06:27,973
Imagining another's thoughts and feelings.

50
00:06:30,156 --> 00:06:32,399
Adopting the posture of another.

51
00:06:34,663 --> 00:06:36,966
Actually feeling as another does.

52
00:06:39,288 --> 00:06:43,495
Imagining how one would feel or think in another's place.

53
00:06:46,519 --> 00:06:49,302
Feeling distress at another's suffering.

54
00:06:52,084 --> 00:07:13,771
feeling for another's suffering sometimes called pity or compassion and finally projecting oneself into another's situation so people use this word in with various things the um that one about actually feeling as another does i think it's a dodgy one isn't it

55
00:07:14,478 --> 00:07:23,954
I mean, if you have, say, some great sorrow and the person you're telling that to say to them, oh, I know exactly what you feel.

56
00:07:24,714 --> 00:07:30,004
Well, I mean, it's a bit of a jump, isn't it?

57
00:07:30,024 --> 00:07:35,894
And the other one about feeling distress at another's suffering sounds a bit like reactivity.

58
00:07:36,274 --> 00:07:38,257
You know, it's like you're reacting to it.

59
00:07:41,444 --> 00:07:54,742
So there's all sorts of definitions for this empathy, but basically I think it differs from sympathy in that there's a heart, a heart connection, a greater heart connection.

60
00:07:54,762 --> 00:08:05,798
One definition was the ability to appreciate the other person's feelings without becoming so emotionally involved that your judgment is affected.

61
00:08:05,947 --> 00:08:14,737
And I think that's the danger with empathy, that the emotional part overrides your rational part.

62
00:08:14,838 --> 00:08:16,139
There's got to be a balance there.

63
00:08:18,122 --> 00:08:30,516
If you just think about this recent case of this little poor five-year-old boy who fell down a well in Morocco, hundreds of people watching online, hundreds of people turned up, thousands watching online.

64
00:08:30,536 --> 00:08:32,239
It became worldwide news.

65
00:08:33,399 --> 00:08:35,042
And yet, as I've mentioned every day,

66
00:08:35,326 --> 00:09:01,602
10 000 children are dying of hunger or hunger related causes so there's a point where you know something touches you very greatly and uh and it becomes a sort of obsession really now you might not feel empathy for various reasons one of them is you know fear and aversion towards another suffering um

67
00:09:01,988 --> 00:09:31,235
that keeps you away from it and and if that comes to us then really we have to do a bit of vipassana on it and wait for it to pass and make that effort to connect um i was once walking on on the main road this is going back many many years and um a dog had been knocked over it was dark at night and uh it was obviously in agony and whoever had knocked it over and put it under a tree

68
00:09:31,721 --> 00:09:34,966
And I was with my ex-wife at that time.

69
00:09:35,787 --> 00:09:40,772
And I went to try and make the dog comfortable.

70
00:09:41,192 --> 00:09:48,500
And as I lifted it a little bit to try and get it into a better position, it just grimaced with this dreadful pain.

71
00:09:49,523 --> 00:09:51,544
And I didn't know what to do, really.

72
00:09:51,845 --> 00:09:53,847
So we just left it.

73
00:09:54,508 --> 00:09:58,572
I mean, these days, of course, with mobiles, you'd have got in touch with the RSPCA.

74
00:09:59,330 --> 00:10:05,360
But it was imprinted on my mind, the dreadful agony that this poor dog was in.

75
00:10:08,544 --> 00:10:15,356
The other thing is pity.

76
00:10:16,658 --> 00:10:19,263
Pity is feeling sorry for someone.

77
00:10:19,924 --> 00:10:23,750
It's really coming from a place of conceit.

78
00:10:24,456 --> 00:10:43,815
know and it stops you really feeling what you're really what you're really hiding your feeling for that person by covering it over with a sense of being sorry for someone well if i mean we've all i'm sure had that experience of somebody feeling sorry for us it's not very helpful

79
00:10:44,486 --> 00:10:54,840
But it's one way that we can, as it were, bypass that feeling of being connected to somebody's suffering if it's something that we find very difficult to be with.

80
00:10:57,663 --> 00:10:59,705
And the final thing is moral outrage.

81
00:11:01,668 --> 00:11:06,634
You know, people being outraged by the dreadful things that are going on in society and things like that.

82
00:11:07,674 --> 00:11:12,620
And I was just reading that there are recent studies where

83
00:11:13,495 --> 00:11:39,164
for for celebrities it's very good for publicity to be morally outraged and then social media content loves it sharing retreat retweeting it expressing this tremendous moral outrage but it often often sort of disguises a sense of insecurity about one's own moral standing it seems

84
00:11:39,634 --> 00:11:48,967
So if you find yourself being morally outraged, just hang on in there for a minute and just ask yourself, well, where's this outrage coming from and how is it helpful?

85
00:11:49,688 --> 00:11:53,754
In Buddhist understanding, rage doesn't really help.

86
00:11:54,235 --> 00:11:57,678
It only clouds our minds, clouds our hearts.

87
00:12:00,023 --> 00:12:09,134
And then, so finally, if the empathy has force behind it, then there'll be a sort of...

88
00:12:10,312 --> 00:12:40,302
a demand really within ourselves to do something and that's when we enter into some sort of compassionate action um i just think you have to be very careful there isn't it because often people get burnt out with this stuff being not recognizing that that difference between what you can do and what you want to do who you can influence and who you can't influence

89
00:12:40,434 --> 00:12:50,908
And if you try to do something which is not within your power or your area of influence, then obviously you're just going to end up burning out.

90
00:12:50,928 --> 00:12:53,993
You're going to end up feeling disappointed, depressed and all that.

91
00:12:56,375 --> 00:12:58,759
I've used the word depressed there, which I don't like.

92
00:12:58,839 --> 00:12:59,860
It medicalizes it.

93
00:13:01,022 --> 00:13:03,125
More like disheartened would be a better word, I think.

94
00:13:03,485 --> 00:13:04,285
Down in the dumps.

95
00:13:07,210 --> 00:13:10,053
Here's a little thing that might be of interest.

96
00:13:10,523 --> 00:13:38,657
um when you if you're a bit down in the dumps and you feel a bit low you might give yourself a little present you know and that makes you feel happy it lifts you a little bit i suppose it comes to um what they call it retail therapy or something but how interesting it is that when you see somebody who's a bit down in the mouth and you want to give them a bit of a lift doing a little kindness to them your happiness stays much longer

97
00:13:39,784 --> 00:13:50,660
And it tells us about how we relate to each other and how important it is for us to have that sort of kind relationship.

98
00:13:57,551 --> 00:14:05,602
So I just want to end with just this little occasion that happened to me and what responses I might have given.

99
00:14:05,984 --> 00:14:07,505
I won't tell you which one I did.

100
00:14:08,267 --> 00:14:09,589
That wouldn't be fair.

101
00:14:10,615 --> 00:14:38,951
i got on a bus once and there was and i sat next to this elderly man again this is going back years and his face was very badly injured and scarred and bruised and uh i happened you know i asked him i said i said what happened and he said he'd been worrying about his rent and he walked out in the road and got knocked over got knocked down so i mean i could have said things like well that's bad news well that's what happens when you get worried you see

102
00:14:40,096 --> 00:14:41,076
Well, at least you weren't killed.

103
00:14:45,683 --> 00:14:53,075
I could say something like, well, I'm very sorry to hear that, but you know, the Citizens Advice Bureau, they can really help you with money problems.

104
00:14:54,998 --> 00:14:57,962
That would be particularly helpful.

105
00:14:59,125 --> 00:15:01,467
I might say, well, that's really terrible.

106
00:15:01,707 --> 00:15:03,150
I'm so sorry to hear it.

107
00:15:03,311 --> 00:15:04,753
I do hope you heal quickly.

108
00:15:08,732 --> 00:15:10,655
I might say, I'm very saddened.

109
00:15:10,917 --> 00:15:11,938
I'm saddened to hear what you say.

110
00:15:11,999 --> 00:15:13,881
It's a pretty terrible experience.

111
00:15:13,902 --> 00:15:15,004
How are you feeling now?

112
00:15:15,043 --> 00:15:16,807
Are you getting treatment?

113
00:15:17,769 --> 00:15:20,693
Are your rent troubles getting sorted?

114
00:15:21,174 --> 00:15:23,960
And I hope you heal up quickly.

115
00:15:24,280 --> 00:15:26,183
I've had that little bit of conversation.

116
00:15:27,186 --> 00:15:28,969
I might leave him cheered up a bit.

117
00:15:34,315 --> 00:15:44,548
But then you might step over that line and you might be saying things, the similar things, but then you say to him, have you asked, do you know where to go for help?

118
00:15:45,028 --> 00:15:48,139
And then you suggest, you know, the Citizens Advice Bureau.

119
00:15:49,267 --> 00:16:06,051
And then you might go a step further, which takes you a little bit into do-gooding, where you say, you know, listen, what I'll do is I'll get in touch with the Citizens Advice Bureau for you and I'll get you to meet them and I'll take you there and do this and do that, whether the person wants it or not.

120
00:16:07,072 --> 00:16:08,573
So this is do-gooding.

121
00:16:08,774 --> 00:16:16,404
A do-gooder is a person who does you the good they want to do you, whether you want it or not, whether you need it or not.

122
00:16:17,379 --> 00:16:21,889
So there's all these various ways that we can relate to somebody's suffering.

123
00:16:24,254 --> 00:16:37,160
Anyway, I hope that gives some food for thought and just allows us, I think, not to fall into, I think,

124
00:16:37,782 --> 00:16:38,462
What can we say?

125
00:16:38,482 --> 00:16:44,227
Not to feel that we have to always do something about somebody's suffering.

126
00:16:44,928 --> 00:16:47,912
We're limited by our circumstance.

127
00:16:48,613 --> 00:16:55,158
And not to feel that we always have to be deeply empathetic every time we hear somebody's suffering.

128
00:16:56,220 --> 00:16:58,522
I just think that sort of burns out.

129
00:17:01,524 --> 00:17:04,228
And that there's a place for just ordinary sympathy.

130
00:17:07,144 --> 00:17:09,329
I don't know whether you agree with me or not.

131
00:17:10,191 --> 00:17:25,001
Anyway, I hope my words have been of some assistance and that by your wise choice between sympathy, empathy and compassion, you will release yourself from all suffering sooner rather than later.

